The type of tree will vary depending on your location. The most important characteristic of the bark is that it is dry. Break off the inner bark and shred or break it into small strips or chips, depending on the strength of the wood. Do not strip bark unless absolutely necessary. Cutting bark can damage or kill trees. Ideally, pick bark that is on dead trees, on the ground, or the like. Peeling bark off trees should only be done in an actual emergency. Different barks burn differently. As natural material, they also will burn differently depending on your environment, the season, and in your weather conditions. Choose cedar, if possible. You can spot a cedar tree by its reddish-brown fibrous bark that is easy to shred with your hands. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/05/Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/05/Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Cut off a chunk of cottonwood bark with whatever sharp tool you have and whittle away the outer bark until you can see the cord-like strands on the inside. Cottonwood bark has a soft characteristic that can, like cedar bark, be stripped into small pieces. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3f/Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3f/Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Cattails are common throughout Europe and America and are abundant around swamps and ponds.You want to use the bushy, cotton-like material on the top of the stem which flourishes in the fall as the plant goes to seed. Simply snap it off and ignite. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5f/Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5f/Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

In mid to late summer, cattails bloom into a brown sausage-shaped substance on the top of the cattail. This part of the plant works for tinder as well. Snap it off and break or cut it open to get to the driest material possible. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/43/Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/43/Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Cut off a large piece and break it into smaller chunks if it is sufficiently dry. Tinder fungus predominantly grows on birch trees, which can be identified by their white bark, and has the appearance of a chunk of burnt or blackened crusty bark. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/af/Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/af/Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If the material is wet, you can slowly air-dry the fungus over time for later use. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/fd/Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/fd/Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

This material is an invaluable resource to take with you when you venture into the outdoors.Place several small squares (about one square inch in size) of cotton fabric into an airtight container that can withstand heat, such as a metal water bottle. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a3/Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-6Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a3/Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-6Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Set the container atop an already flaming fire for about five minutes. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5e/Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-6Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-6Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5e/Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-6Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-6Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Remove the container from the fire using tongs and allow to cool. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b2/Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-6Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-6Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b2/Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-6Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-6Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Open the container and observe the squares. They should be blackened in color. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/42/Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-6Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-6Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/42/Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-6Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Tinder-for-a-Fire-Step-6Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
